# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->

# Approach
The code starts with a helper function GetLength which recursively calculates the length of the linked list. It traverses the list until it reaches the end (NULL) and returns the count of nodes encountered.

The rotateRight function takes the head of the linked list and the rotation value k as input. It performs the following steps:

Check for base cases:

If the head is NULL or k is 0, return the head as no rotation is needed.
If the length of the list is 1, return the head as there's only one node and no rotation can be performed.
Calculate the length of the list by calling the GetLength helper function.

Adjust k to be within the range of the list length by taking the modulus (k % length).

Perform the rotation k % length times:

Start a loop from 0 to k % length - 1.
Initialize a pointer p to the head of the list.
Traverse the list until p reaches the second-to-last node (p->next->next == NULL).
Create a new node a using dynamic memory allocation (malloc) and assign the value of the last node (p->next->val) to it.
Set the next pointer of a to the current head of the list (a->next = head).
Update the head to be the new node a (head = a).
Set the next pointer of the second-to-last node (p->next) to NULL to disconnect the last node from the list.
Return the new head of the rotated list.

The time complexity of the code is O(n), where n is the length of the linked list. This is because we traverse the list twice: once to calculate the length and again to perform the rotation. The space complexity is O(1) as we are using a constant amount of additional space for the pointers and variables.








# Complexity
- Time complexity:
O(n)
- Space complexity:
O(n)
# Code
```
/**
 * Definition for singly-linked list.
 * struct ListNode {
 *     int val;
 *     struct ListNode *next;
 * };
 */
 int GetLength(struct ListNode* head)
{
	if (head == NULL)
		return 0;

	return 1 + GetLength(head->next);
}
struct ListNode* rotateRight(struct ListNode* head, int k){
        if (head == NULL || k == 0)
		return head;
    int length = GetLength(head);

	if (length == 1)
		return head;
    for(int i=0;i<k%length;i++)
    {
        struct ListNode *p=head;
        while(p->next->next!=NULL)
        {
            p=p->next;
        }
        struct ListNode *a=(struct ListNode *)malloc(sizeof(struct ListNode));
        a->val=p->next->val;
        a->next=head;
        head=a;
        p->next=NULL;
    }
    return head;

}
```

