solutions.content:
In this problem, we need to find the convex hull of all the *trees*. But the twist is that we also need to include the ***collinear*** points on the convex hull in our answer, which in most implementations are ignored as typical implementations find the minimum number of points for the convex hull.

1. **Using Jarvis March Algorithm**
To solve this we can store the *collinear point in a different list* and when the ***orientation*** changes we push the collinear points upto now in the answer *set*.
Time Complexity: `O(h*n)` where h is the number of points on the *convex hull*
Space Complexity: `O(n)`
Runtime: `14ms`
Beats: `91.94%`
***Code:***  
```
class Solution {
    public int[][] outerTrees(int[][] trees) {
        Set<HullPoint> hull = new HashSet<>();
        List<HullPoint> collinear = new ArrayList<>();
        HullPoint[] a = new HullPoint[trees.length];
        for(int i=0;i<trees.length;i++) {
            //make a new array of hullpoint objects using trees array
            a[i] = new HullPoint(trees[i][0], trees[i][1]);
        }
        HullPoint curr = a[0];
        //find hullpoint with smallest x-coordinate
        for(int i=0;i<a.length;i++) {
            if(a[i].x < curr.x) {
                curr = a[i];
            }
        }
        //store the starting tree
        HullPoint start = curr;

        do {
            hull.add(curr);
            HullPoint next = a[0];
            for(int i=0;i<a.length;i++) {
                HullPoint point = a[i];
                if(point.equals(curr))
                    continue;
                int orientation = getOrientation(curr, next, point);
                //counter-clockwise or next == curr
                if(orientation > 0 || next.equals(curr)) {
                    next = point;
                    collinear.clear();
                }else if(orientation == 0) {//collinear
                    //set next to farthest point and push middle point to collinear list
                    if(getDistance(curr, next) < getDistance(curr, point)) {
                        collinear.add(next);
                        next = point;
                    }else {
                        collinear.add(point);
                    }
                }
            }
            //add collinear points to convex hull
            hull.addAll(collinear);
            curr = next;
        }while(!curr.equals(start) && hull.size() != a.length);

        //converting our set convex hull to required array output form
        int size = hull.size();
        List<HullPoint> temp = hull.stream().toList();
        int[][] ans = new int[size][2];

        for(int i=0;i<size;i++) {
            ans[i][0] = temp.get(i).x;
            ans[i][1] = temp.get(i).y;
        }
        return ans;
    }
    /**
    * Finds the orientation of three HullPoints
    */
    static int getOrientation(HullPoint start, HullPoint middle, HullPoint last) {
        int temp = (
            ((last.y - start.y) * (middle.x - start.x)) - 
            ((middle.y - start.y) * (last.x - start.x))
            );
        return temp;    
    }
    /**
    * Finds the euclidean distance between two HullPoints
    */
    static double getDistance(HullPoint a, HullPoint b) {
        double distance = Math.sqrt(
            ((a.x - b.x) * (a.x - b.x)) + 
            ((a.y - b.y) * (a.y - b.y))
            );
        return distance;
    }
    /**
    *User-Defined class for Convex HullPoints with their x and y coordinates
    */
    static class HullPoint {
        int x;
        int y;

        HullPoint(int x, int y) {
            this.x = x;
            this.y = y;
        }

        public boolean equals(HullPoint h) {
            return this.x == h.x && this.y == h.y;
        }
    }
}
```

2. **Using Graham-Scan Algorithm**
Time Complexity: `O(n*log(n))` 
Space Complexity: `O(n)`
Runtime: `16ms`
Beats: `91.94%`
***Code:***
```
class Solution {
    public int[][] outerTrees(int[][] trees) {
        HullPoint[] a = new HullPoint[trees.length];
        for(int i=0;i<trees.length;i++) {
            //make a new array of hullpoint objects using trees array
            a[i] = new HullPoint(trees[i][0], trees[i][1]);
        }
        //Start with the tree with minimum y coordinate
        HullPoint[] start = {a[0]};
        for(int i=1;i<a.length;i++) {
            if(a[i].y < start[0].y) {
                start[0] = a[i];
            }
        }

        //Sort the points first on the basis of polar angle and then on the basis of distance from starting point
        Arrays.sort(a, (a1, a2) -> {
            int temp = getOrientation(start[0], a1, a2);
            if(temp < 0)
                return 1;
            else if(temp > 0)
                return -1;
            else
                return Double.compare(getDistance(a1, start[0]), getDistance(a2, start[0]));
        });

        ArrayDeque<HullPoint> ad = new ArrayDeque<>();
        //Find points with same polar angle as the last point
        int left = a.length - 1;
        while (left >= 0 && getOrientation(start[0], a[a.length - 1], a[left]) == 0) {
            left--;
        }
        left++;
        int right = a.length - 1;
        //reverse them
        while(left < right) {
            HullPoint temp = a[left];
            a[left] = a[right];
            a[right] = temp;
            left++;
            right--;
        }
        //typical graham-scan 
        for(int i=0;i<a.length;i++) {
            while(ad.size() >= 2) {
                HullPoint last = ad.pop();
                HullPoint secondLast = ad.pop();

                if(getOrientation(secondLast, last, a[i]) < 0) {
                    ad.push(secondLast);
                }else {
                    ad.push(secondLast);
                    ad.push(last);
                    break;
                }
            }
            ad.push(a[i]);
        }
        //copy the stack to answer array
        int k = ad.size();
        int[][] ans = new int[k][2];
        k--;

        while(!ad.isEmpty()) {
            HullPoint h = ad.pop();
            ans[k][0] = h.x;
            ans[k][1] = h.y;
            k--;
        }
        return ans;
    }
    /**
    * Finds the orientation of three HullPoints
    */
    static int getOrientation(HullPoint start, HullPoint middle, HullPoint last) {
        int temp = (
            ((last.y - start.y) * (middle.x - start.x)) - 
            ((middle.y - start.y) * (last.x - start.x))
            );
        return temp;    
    }
    /**
    * Finds the euclidean distance between two HullPoints
    */
    static double getDistance(HullPoint a, HullPoint b) {
        double distance = Math.sqrt(
            ((a.x - b.x) * (a.x - b.x)) + 
            ((a.y - b.y) * (a.y - b.y))
            );
        return distance;
    }
    /**
    *User-Defined class for Convex HullPoints with their x and y coordinates
    */
    static class HullPoint {
        int x;
        int y;

        HullPoint(int x, int y) {
            this.x = x;
            this.y = y;
        }

        public boolean equals(HullPoint h) {
            return this.x == h.x && this.y == h.y;
        }
    }
}
```

