# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
The leftmost and rightmost point(s) are guarunteed to be in the answer.

Between two guarunteed points, the only point that's guarunteed to also be in the solution set is the one farthest away from the imaginary line between the two guarunteed points (farthest above the line if it's the top of the fence, farthest below the line if it's below the fence).
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
Sort the points by their x-coordinates and add the leftmost and rightmost point (or points there's a tie). Then search between those guarunteed points for the point farthest above the imaginary line.

Using basic algebra, we can find a formula for the distance a point is from the line by finding the intercepting line, then the point of intersection between the lines, and lastly the distance between the intersection and the point.

The imaginary line between the inital two points $$(x_{left},y_{left})$$ and $$(x_{right},y_{right})$$ is 
$$y=m(x-x_{left})+y_{left}$$, where $$m=\dfrac{y_{right}-y_{left}}{x_{right}-x_{left}}$$.
The inverse line that passes through the point being tested $$(x_{test},y_{test})$$ is
$$y=\frac{1}{m}(x-x_{test})+y_{test}$$.
The x-intercept between these lines can be found by finding where the y's match:
$$m(x-x_{left})+y_{left}=\frac{1}{m}(x-x_{test})+y_{test}$$
then solving for x we get
$$x=\dfrac{-x_{test}+m\cdot y_{test}+m^{2}x_{left}-m\cdot y_{left}}{m^{2}-1}$$.
We can get the corresponding y coordinate by simply plugging the x-intercept into either line formula:
$$y=m\left(\left(\dfrac{-x_{test}+my_{test}+m^{2}x_{left}-m\cdot y_{left}}{m^{2}-1}\right)-x_{left}\right)+y_{left}$$
which can be simplified to
$$y=\dfrac{m^{2}y_{test}+mx_{left}-mx_{test}-y_{left}}{m^{2}-1}$$.
The difference formula is just the hypotenuse of the differences-between-each-axis sides. Here, that looks like this:
$$d=\sqrt{\left(x_{test}-\dfrac{m^{2}\cdot x_{left}-m\cdot y_{left}+m\cdot y_{test}+x_{test}}{m^{2}+1}\right)^{2}+\left(y_{test}-\dfrac{-m\cdot x_{left}+m^{2}\cdot y_{test}+m\cdot x_{test}+y_{left}}{m^{2}+1}\right)^{2}}$$
but luckily that mess can be simplified down to
$$d=\sqrt{\dfrac{\left(m\left(x_{left}-x_{test}\right)-y_{left}+y_{test}\right)^{2}}{m^{2}+1}}$$.
We can tweak to this formula by bringing out the numerator
$$d=\left(m\left(x_{left}-x_{test}\right)-y_{left}+y_{test}\right)\cdot\sqrt{\dfrac{1}{m^{2}+1}}$$
which will make the formula compute the same thing, except the output will be negative if the test point is below the imaginary line, which in our case is very useful.
The main downsize to this formula is having the compute the inverse square root at the end, but luckily since m is always the same when testing against the imaginary line, $\sqrt{\dfrac{1}{m^{2}+1}}$ is just a constant (positive) multiplier and we can simply take it out without our ability to find the point that's farthest away.
After all that, our final formula is
$$d=m\left(x_{left}-x_{test}\right)-y_{left}+y_{test}$$.

Using this formula, we can test to see which point between the left and right points is farthest above the line. If there is one, add it to the answer and then do the checking again for the points between the left point and the newly added point, and the newly added point and the right point. 

After all possible points are added this way, do the same thing but for finding the points on the bottom (aka points farthest below the imaginary lines). After that we're done!

(The only edge cases we have to account for are cases where there are ties for the leftmost and rightmost points at the very start. In these cases, just add all the points to the answer and start searching for points between the top left and top right points, and the bottom left and bottom right points for the bottom of the fence.)

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
$O(n^2)$, though usually much better.

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
$O(n)$ for storing the sorted list and the output (although you can use the original list to store the output after it's been sorted).
# Code
```
/**
 * Return an array of arrays of size *returnSize.
 * The sizes of the arrays are returned as *returnColumnSizes array.
 * Note: Both returned array and *columnSizes array must be malloced, assume caller calls free().
 */
void recurse(int** trees,short left,short right,int** output, int* returnSize, bool mode){
    if (left+1==right || trees[left][0]==trees[right][0]) return;//if no points to add, or all on a vertical line
    float slope=(float)(trees[right][1]-trees[left][1])/(float)(trees[right][0]-trees[left][0]);
    float far=(mode?-1:1);
    int farInd;
    for (short i=left+1;trees[i][0]<trees[right][0];i++){//finds tree furthest from line between tree[left] and tree[right]
        if (trees[i][0]==trees[left][0]) continue;//guarunteed not to add
        float temp=slope*(trees[left][0]-trees[i][0])-trees[left][1]+trees[i][1];//modified distance-to-line formula
        if ((temp>far && mode) || (temp<far && !mode)){
            far=temp;
            farInd=i;
        }
    }
    if ((far>=0 && mode) || (far<=0 && !mode)){//mode 1: top of rope, mode 2: bottom
        output[(*returnSize)++]=trees[farInd];
        recurse(trees,left,farInd,output,returnSize,mode);//check left of new anchor point for more anchor points
        recurse(trees,farInd,right,output,returnSize,mode);//check right of new anchor point
    }
}
